article.headline: Lennox's late 3-pointer propels Storm to sixth straight win
article.linkText: Lennox weathers injury, lifts Storm past Sparks
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Betty Lennox's jump shot didn't reveal how much
her wrist hurt.

Lennox made a 3-pointer with 27.4 seconds left, and Seattle won
its franchise-record tying sixth straight Sunday night, 77-72 over
the Los Angeles Sparks.

"I tried not to show it, but I'm out there playing in a lot of
pain," Lennox said. "Forty minutes, that's what I tried to focus
my mind on, and after 40 minutes, then I can go home and cry."

Seattle (14-10) held a 71-70 lead, when Lennox -- who has
tendinitis in her wrist -- knocked down her fifth basket to stretch
the Storm's lead to four points.

Tamika Whitmore made two free throws with 23.5 seconds left to
get the Sparks within two.

Seattle's Lauren Jackson then made one of two free throws with
10.7 seconds remaining, but Janell Burse got the offensive rebound.
She got the ball to Lennox, who was fouled and made two free throws
to seal the Storm's victory.

"Betty's 3 is what everyone will talk about, but [Burse's]
offensive rebound was huge," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said.

Los Angeles (11-12) has lost five of six.

Lennox's injury flared up in the last week and she attempted
only two shots in Seattle's win over Charlotte on Friday. She has
received one cortisone shot and is taking pain medication.

With the wrist heavily taped, Lennox finished with 17 points on
5-of-13 shooting, and had a large bag of ice on the injury
afterward.

"Tendinitis, you can't snap your fingers and it'll go away. ...
Right now it hurts pretty bad," Lennox said.

Jackson had 17 points and 10 rebounds. Burse scored 13 and Sue
Bird had 12, including the 200th 3-pointer of her career.

Lisa Leslie and Chamique Holdsclaw tried to carry the Sparks in
the final minutes, scoring 14 of Los Angeles' final 16 points.

Leslie tied a WNBA record for most field goals made without a
miss, shooting 8-for-8, and finishing with 18 points. Holdsclaw had
17, and Laura Macchi added 10.

But Seattle dominated the glass, outrebounding Los Angeles 37-20
and 23-17 on second-chance points.

"Just rebounding. That's our Achilles' heel this year and
that's something we really have to continue working on," Leslie
said. "That's the game right there."

Another factor was free throw shooting.

The teams combined to commit 44 fouls -- 29 by the Sparks.
Seattle took advantage by outscoring Los Angeles 28-10 at the free
throw line.

That advantage made up for a tough night of 3-point shooting for
the Storm. Seattle had been shooting 45 percent from behind the arc
during the streak but made only 33 percent against Los Angeles.

"It looks like a cat attacked me. It was pretty physical,"
Jackson said, looking at scratches on her arms. "It's really tough
to get into the flow of the game when you don't know what's going
to be called."

Seattle fell to 8-10 after a loss to Washington on July 13. But
the Storm have matched their six-game winning streak of last year
and moved into a tie with Houston for second place in the Western
Conference.

Los Angeles is under .500 for the first time since June 8 when
it lost to Phoenix 66-63 and dropped to 3-4. The Sparks have not
had a losing record this late in the season since 1998, when they
finished 12-18.

"I thought we did a lot of good things that we haven't done on
the road," Los Angeles coach Henry Bibby said. "The discrepancy
in foul shots ... that's a big difference. We never got into the
bonus, so we never had a chance."

Sparks point guard Nikki Teasley missed her fourth straight game
with a foot injury.
